competing risks data analysis via a Multinomial GLMM

Henrique Ap. Laureano

Last modification on 2020-05-16 12:02:11

We want to model the Cumulative Incidence Function (CIF) in this specific manner, \[ F_{k} (t \mid X, \eta_{k}, u_{1}, u_{2}) = \underbrace{\pi_{k}(X, u_{1}, u_{2})}_{ \substack{\text{cluster-specific}\\ \text{risk level}} }\times \underbrace{\Phi[w_{k} g(t) - X^{\top}\gamma_{k} - \eta_{k}]}_{ \substack{\text{cluster-specific}\\ \text{failure time trajectory}} }, \quad k = 1, 2. \] i.e., in a cluster-specific fashion - in other words, we introduce latent effects in the model structure.

By the specification above is clear that were setting a structure for two failure causes, a third one is left to accommodate the censorship. In summary, well deal with a Multinomial of three classes.

math

For a subject \(i\), with cluster \(j\), in the time \(t\), we have \[ y_{i j t} \mid u_{1j}, u_{2j}, \eta_{1j}, \eta_{2j} \sim \text{Multinomial}(p_{1ijt}, p_{2ijt}, p_{3ijt}), \] \[ \begin{align} \text{with} \quad \bm{r} = \begin{bmatrix} u_{1j}\\ u_{2j}\\ \eta_{1j}\\ \eta_{2j} \end{bmatrix} &\sim \mathcal{N} \left[\begin{bmatrix} 0\\ 0\\ 0\\ 0\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} \sigma_{u_{1}}^{2} & \varrho_{u_{1}, u_{2}} & \varrho_{u_{1}, \eta_{1}} & \varrho_{u_{1}, \eta_{2}}\\ & \sigma_{u_{2}}^{2} & \varrho_{u_{2}, \eta_{1}} & \varrho_{u_{2}, \eta_{2}}\\ & & \sigma_{\eta_{1}}^{2} & \varrho_{\eta_{1}, \eta_{2}}\\ & & & \sigma_{\eta_{2}}^{2} \end{bmatrix}\right],\\ \text{and} \quad p_{kijt} &= \frac{\exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\}}{ 1 + \sum_{m=1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{mij} \bm{\beta}_{mi} + u_{mj}\}} w_{k}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{k} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{kij}\bm{\gamma}_{ki} - \eta_{kj}]. \end{align} \]

The likelihood for a random sample, and \(\bm{\theta} = [\bm{\beta}, \bm{\gamma}, \bm{w}, \bm{\sigma^{2}}, \bm{\varrho}]^{\top}\), is given by \[ L(\bm{\theta}; y) = \prod_{j=1}^{J} \int_{\Re^{4}} \prod_{i=1}^{n_{j}} \prod_{t=1}^{n_{ij}} \Bigg[\binom{n_{ijt}}{y_{1ijt}, y_{2ijt}, y_{3ijt}} \prod_{k=1}^{K} p_{kijt}^{y_{kijt}} \Bigg] (2\pi)^{-2} |Q|^{1/2} \exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2} \bm{r}_{j}^{\top} Q \bm{r}_{j} \right\}\text{d}\bm{r}_{j}. \] i.e., \[ L(\bm{\theta}; y_{j}) = \int_{\Re^{4}} \pi(y_{j} \mid \bm{r}_{j})~\pi(\bm{r}_{j}) ~\text{d}\bm{r}_{j}. \]

data

J <- 1e4 ## clusters
I <- 2 ## subjects by cluster
k <- 3 ## classes, i.e., k-1 diseases and the censorship
E <- matrix(c(1, .4, .5, .4,
              0,  1, .4, .3,
              0,  0,  1, .4,
              0,  0,  0,  1), nrow = 4, byrow = TRUE)
## this is the easiest way that I thought to build a symmetric matrix -
## like the matrix dimension increases, this approach shows to be the
## easiest one
E[lower.tri(E, diag = TRUE)] <- t(E)[lower.tri(E, diag = TRUE)]

set.seed(1220)
df <- datasetup(J, I, k, E)

preds <- list(y1 ~ 1, y2 ~ 1)
coefs <- list(beta = c("b01" = -1.9, "b02" = -0.2),
              gama = c("g01" =  1.0, "g02" =  1.2))

Xbeta <- Xcoef(preds, coefs['beta'], data = df)
Xgama <- Xcoef(preds, coefs['gama'], data = df)

probs <- risklevel(Xbeta,
                   u = df %>% select(str_subset(names(df), "^u\\d")))
apply(probs, 2, summary)

Max.    0.670464011 0.96210336 0.96045564
set.seed(0056)
df[ , paste0("y", seq(k))] <- rmultinomial(J * I, 1, prob = probs)
apply(df[ , paste0("y", seq(k))], 2, table)

set.seed(0003)
times <- failuretimes(Xgama,
                      e = df %>% select(str_subset(names(df), "^e\\d")),
                      delta = 80)
df$t <- rowSums(times * df %>% select(str_subset(names(df), "^y\\d")))

if (nrow(df %>% filter(y1 == 1 & t >= 80) %>% select(t)) >= 1) {
    df <- df %>% mutate(y3 = replace(y3, y1 == 1 & t >= 80, 1),
                        y1 = replace(y1, y1 == 1 & t >= 80, 0))
}
if (nrow(df %>% filter(y2 == 1 & t >= 80) %>% select(t)) >= 1) {
    df <- df %>% mutate(y3 = replace(y3, y2 == 1 & t >= 80, 1),
                        y2 = replace(y2, y2 == 1 & t >= 80, 0))
}
print(cbind(df %>% filter(y1 == 1) %>% select(t) %>% summary(),
            df %>% filter(y2 == 1) %>% select(t) %>% summary(),
            df %>% filter(y3 == 1) %>% select(t) %>% summary()),
      quote = FALSE)

optimization

What we have here is an augmented likelihood (multinomial likelihood times a multivariate normal distribution for the random effects), so the first step is to integrate out these random effects - together, \(u\)s and \(\eta\)s.

We know, since we simulate it, that these random effects are from a distribution with mean zero. Therefore, a Newton-Raphson algorithm is a good choice here. This is what we do next.

The Newton-Raphson algorithm has the following scheme \[ \bm{r}_{n+1} = \bm{r}_{n} - \bm{l}^{''} (\bm{r}_{n})^{-1} \bm{l}^{'} (\bm{r}_{n}), \] that is performed until convergence and with \(\bm{l}\) being the augmented log-likelihood.

To speed up the convergence and numerical stability, I computed by hand the gradient, \[ \begin{aligned} \bm{l}^{'} (u_{kj}) &= y_{kij} \frac{1 + \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{mij} \bm{\beta}_{mi} + u_{mj}\} }{1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\}}\\ &- \left( \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} y_{mij} \right) \frac{\exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\} }{1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\}}\\ &- y_{Kij} \frac{1}{1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} } \Bigg(\\ & \frac{w_{k}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{k}\text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{kij}\bm{\gamma}_{ki} - \eta_{kj} ] \exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\} \left(1 + \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{mij} \bm{\beta}_{mi} + u_{mj}\} \right)}{ 1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} (1 - w_{n}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{n} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{nij}\bm{\gamma}_{ni} - \eta_{nj}])}\\ &- \frac{\exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\} \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} w_{m}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{m}\text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{mij}\bm{\gamma}_{mi} - \eta_{mj} ] \exp\{\bm{x}_{mij} \bm{\beta}_{mi} + u_{mj}\}}{ 1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} (1 - w_{n}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{n} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{nij}\bm{\gamma}_{ni} - \eta_{nj}])} \Bigg)\\ &- e_{k}^{\top} \bm{Qr},\\ %% -------------------------------------------------------------------- \bm{l}^{'} (\eta_{kj}) &= y_{kij} (w_{k} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - 2t^{2}} (w_{k} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{kij}\bm{\gamma}_{ki} - \eta_{kj}) \phi[w_{k} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{kij}\bm{\gamma}_{ki} - \eta_{kj} ]}{ 1 - \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \frac{\exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} }{1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} } w_{n}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - 2t^{2}} \phi[w_{n} \text{arctanh}\left(\frac{t-\delta/2}{\delta/2}\right) - \bm{x}_{nij}\bm{\gamma}_{ni} - \eta_{nj} ]}\\ &- e_{k}^{\top} \bm{Qr}. \end{aligned} \] and the hessian, \[ \begin{aligned} \bm{l}^{''} (u_{kj}) &= - \frac{\left( \sum_{k = 1}^{K-1} y_{kij} \right) \exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\} \left( 1 + \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{mij} \bm{\beta}_{mi} + u_{mj}\} \right)}{\left( 1 + \sum_{n = 1}^{K-1} \exp\{\bm{x}_{nij} \bm{\beta}_{ni} + u_{nj}\} \right)^{2}}\\ &+ \frac{y_{Kij} \exp\{\bm{x}_{kij} \bm{\beta}_{ki} + u_{kj}\} \sum_{m \neq k}^{K-1} w_{m}\frac{\delta}{2\delta t - of the marginal

An important topic to discuss now is the parametrization. Now, without covariates, we have sixteen parameters (this is a lot)! And most of these are parameters of variance-covariance, i.e.parameters that are complicated to estimate.

Ah, and we have sixteen parameters because we chose to estimate the covariances instead of the correlations, which would increase the number of parameters in the model.

The problem with correlation parameters is that theyre constrained to the interval -1 and 1. A reparametrization with the goal of contour this problem is well known, however, if we model the covariance matrix we still have to invert it in the computation of the multivariate normal density. To skip this inversion we model directly the inverse of the covariance matrix, i.e.the precision matrix. But this creates a new problem.

If we model the entries of the precision matrix we dont know which transformation to use and (important point) we cant guarantee the positive-definiteness of that matrix during the optimization routine. When working with the variance-covariance matrix a smart choice is to work with it Cholesky decomposition, were we then estimate its entries. But what to do when we work with its inverse, the precision matrix? We try here two approaches: the modified Cholesky decomposition and a decomposition based on TMB's unstructured correlation matrix.

Modified Cholesky decomposition:

Starting by what is simpler. The Cholesky decomposition of the variance-covariance matrix \(\Sigma\) is given by \(\Sigma = C C^{\top}\), with \(C\) being a lower-triangular matrix. The modified Cholesky decomposition of the precision matrix \(Q\) is given by \[ Q = T^{\top} (D^{2})^{-1} T, \] with \(D = \text{diag}(C)\) and \(T = D C^{-1}\). i.e., \[ \begin{aligned} Q &= T^{\top} (D^{2})^{-1} T\\ Q &= C^{-\top} D^{\top} D^{-1} D^{-1} D C^{-1}\\ Q &= C^{-\top} I I C^{-1}\\ Q &= C^{-\top} C^{-1}\\ Q &= (C C^{\top})^{-1}\\ Q &= \Sigma^{-1}. \end{aligned} \] Ok, what we do with this decomposition and why it is good? Well, we estimate the entries of the lower-triangular matrix \(T\) with unit diagonal and the entries of the diagonal matrix \(D\) (1 over the entries, in reality, since were working with its inverse). This is good for two reasons: 1) the entries that well estimate are unconstrained and 2) this decomposition guarantees that well always have a positive definite matrix. Here we also reparametrize the entries applying the log function, just for stabilization.

Decomposition based on TMB's unstructured correlation matrix:

We just take that unstructured correlation matrix, scale the variances, and invert everything. i.e., \[ \begin{aligned} Q &= (W \Sigma W^{\top})^{-1}\\ Q &= (W D^{-1/2} L L^{\top} D^{-1/2} W^{\top})^{-1}\\ Q &= W^{-\top} D^{1/2} L^{-\top} L^{-1} D^{1/2} W^{-1}. \end{aligned} \]
